column35: Started well but got bored quickly and wanted to move off. Second attempt she lay down immediately where we left her for the duration as it was time for her to do the next section. Officially 3 attempts though as she wasn't asked to lay down.
column40: Wasnt asked to lie down so didnt respond to command but stayed in the down position when asked to stay and didnt break it.
column47: Although her tail was slightly lowered, she was otherwise fine and didn't stir. She jumped up as soon as she clicked that I was asking it of her and she stood still. She wagged her tail at the end so I feel she was happy with me checking her.
column62: Second response - tried to drop fore-body posture to remove tea-towel (as this was successful in the first response). column76: I have marked Diva as indifferent because this would probably be the closest option available to her response. Though Diva wasnt completely indifferent - she didnt show any apprehension or fear, nor did she even approach let alone show high activity. She merely noticed, wagged her tail and moved on without pause.
column79: Diva was well behaved during this exercise with only one hind-quarter shuffle. But from her fixation on the kong, and un-diverted attention (apart from one gaze away) she was clearly very interested in it.
column87: When she retrieved the kong she merely pushed it around with her nose.
column92: While Diva showed interest on initially seeing the dog, she quickly lost interest and decided to rather investigate her surroundings thereafter.
column107: Diva spent most of the time showing stress toward the crate - she began whining almost immediately (and I am sure that this would be her whines rather than the other dog as per the timing of it) and constantly pacing and even barking at times. She lay down at the very end when she gave up sniffing but she was definitely not settled.
column125: I would say she was quite activated and enthused by my reunion even if she didn't stay by my side. Her demeanor changed from distress to happiness and a wagging tail. However, she did tend to pace a little and then come back again.
